C3","C5","C6","C7","C8"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe complement system is a crucial part of innate immunity that enhances pathogen clearance through multiple mechanisms. \u003Cstrong\u003EC3\u003C/strong\u003E is the central component of all complement pathways and is essential for opsonisation. C3b, derived from C3, coats bacteria to facilitate their recognition and ingestion by phagocytes. C3 deficiency therefore leads to severe recurrent bacterial infections due to impaired opsonisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe terminal complement components have different roles:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC5\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EC6\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EC7\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003EC8\u003C/strong\u003E combine with C9 to form the membrane attack complex (MAC). While deficiency of these proteins increases susceptibility to \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria\u003C/em\u003E infections, they do not significantly affect opsonisation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe MAC creates pores in bacterial cell membranes leading to cell lysis, which is distinct from the opsonisation process that marks pathogens for phagocytosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["C3 is the central component of the complement cascade and its deficiency severely impairs opsonisation and bacterial clearance.","Terminal complement components (C5-C9) form the membrane attack complex but are not involved in opsonisation.","Complement-mediated opsonisation occurs when C3b coats bacteria to facilitate phagocytosis."],"references":["Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Okura Y, Kobayashi I, Yamada M, Sasaki S, Yamada Y, Kamioka I, Kanai R, Takahashi Y, Ariga T. Clinical characteristics and genotype-phenotype correlations in C3 deficiency. J Allergy Clin Immunol. 2016 Feb;137(2):640-644.e1. doi: 10.1016/j.jaci.2015.08.017. Epub 2015 Oct 4. PMID: 26435005."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52181"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14995"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52181"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T20:32:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T20:33:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7683"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66728"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4908"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-14T17:03:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-